  "prompt": "Has a game developer set a precedent by allowing others to upload a video to YouTube of a user playing one of his games?",
  "response": "Yes, game developers have allowed and even encouraged players to upload videos of their gameplay to platforms like YouTube. One notable precedent was set by Markus Persson, the creator of Minecraft. He explicitly supported the community in sharing videos, which greatly contributed to the game's popularity.\n\nMoreover, companies like Nintendo, which had historically been stricter with content sharing, began embracing the trend. They launched the Nintendo Creators Program in 2015, allowing creators to monetize videos featuring Nintendo games, although the program was later discontinued in 2018 in favor of more relaxed content guidelines.\n\nOverall, most developers now view gameplay videos, streaming, and Let's Plays as beneficial, recognizing the role they play in marketing and community engagement. However, the specific permissions and monetization rights vary by developer and game, so it's always best to check the terms set by the copyright holders.",
